<div id="review_11623104" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/11623104" />
    <a title="Laurie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/684539-laurie"><img alt="Laurie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1235941962p2/684539.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/11623104?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laurie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laurie" href="/user/show/684539-laurie">Laurie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer11623104" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15807709024405548798">I think a lot of people I know who would read this book would think &quot;Yeah, that makes sense&quot; or &quot;I knew that innately but now here are the words to confirm it.&quot;<br/><br/>I studied Buddhism - among other religions - while in college so the concepts were familiar to me. What I like about this book, though, is that it is clever, has fun and practical anecdotes that are easy to relate to and is a great resource. One to keep in the nightstand and read a bit before bed or in the morning so that every so often, </span>
  <span id="freeText15807709024405548798" style="display:none">I think a lot of people I know who would read this book would think "Yeah, that makes sense" or "I knew that innately but now here are the words to confirm it."<br /><br />I studied Buddhism - among other religions - while in college so the concepts were familiar to me. What I like about this book, though, is that it is clever, has fun and practical anecdotes that are easy to relate to and is a great resource. One to keep in the nightstand and read a bit before bed or in the morning so that every so often, you can look at the Eight Fold path to remind yourself what to do every day, every moment. Confused about priorities and feeling stressed? The Five Remembrances can help bring things into perspective and focus. I used to have the list from the "Mingling Dharma with Your Every Day Life" posted on the fridge to remind me how to "cultivate mindful awareness". </span>
  <a data-text-id="15807709024405548798" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


